        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-33666" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-33666" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I didn&#8217;t choose T-Mobile but I&#8217;m not planning on leaving them any time soon, and mainly BECAUSE they&#8217;re so open to things like cooked ROM usage and tethering without extra charge.  I hardly ever use tethering, so I&#8217;m certainly not going to pay another $30 each month just for the few hundred KB/few MB I might use in that month.  I just did a speed test last night on &#8220;4&#8243;g, and only received at something like 300 kbit per second, so it&#8217;s not like I&#8217;d use their networks for much other than an occasional, small, necessary file transfer or light web browsing.</p>
<p>That said, I&#8217;ve listened to my coworkers and friends who are on other networks.  One of them used to work in Verizon&#8217;s store, and because of Verizon&#8217;s practices &#8212; even to their own employees &#8212; he left them to work for AT&amp;T.  I soon after heard him complaining about AT&amp;T&#8217;s practices &#8212; nowhere near what Verizon was like, but still.  I&#8217;ve also heard a lot of coworkers complain about both of these providers, and I have other friends and family with Sprint who are less than satisfied with their services. </p>
<p>I haven&#8217;t heard any of them complain about T-Mobile.  </p>
<p>Seems to me, T-Mo&#8217;s doing it right, whatever they&#8217;re [not] doing [to their customers].  I wonder how actively they seek out comments like these in forums like these.  Do they know how much they are appreciated for what they do?  Does anybody, like, call them up and thank them?  &#8230;send them letters of appreciation?  &#8230;erect shrines in their honor?</p>
<p>Frankly, I have no reason not to be with T-Mo.  And I second @rickb928 above:  I&#8217;m also using a G1, and while I considered getting a G2, I simply can&#8217;t afford one right now &#8212; even with the subsidy &#8212; and I would feel left out and abandoned as well if it weren&#8217;t for the ability to hack the phone and put FroYo on it.  I think my father in law is still running Donut on his stock G1.  Granted, his is a little less futzy, works a bit more stably, lasts a lot longer on a single charge, and actually still makes and receives calls without fail; but he can&#8217;t tether, can&#8217;t get &#8220;4&#8243;g, and can&#8217;t run several of the apps I use on a regular basis.  Oh, and can&#8217;t get exchange e-mail without paying extra for it, nor sync multiple GMail accounts.  So it&#8217;s a tradeoff, but I like the benefits of running CM6.1 and the drawbacks are fairly few and far between in the stable releases.</p>
<p>A big thanks to Steve and Kompany for all the hard work they do!</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li>
